            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-field-body field--type-text-long field--label-hidden field__item"><h3>Medicine shield workshop</h3>
<p>Friday, August 15 from 1 pm to 2:30 pm<br>
Ages 16 and up.<br>
Cost: $75 + tax (per person) .&nbsp;<a href="https://anc.ca.apm.activecommunities.com/ottawa/activity/search/detail/149104?onlineSiteId=0&amp;locale=en-US&amp;from_original_cui=true"><strong>Advance registration is required.</strong></a></p>
<p>Join <a href="https://www.makatew.ca/">Makatew Workshops</a> at Pinhey's Point Historic Site to create a Medicine Shield, a deeply personal piece rooted in Indigenous tradition. Historically used by warriors and hunters for protection, medicine shields also carried spiritual significance, representing the strengths, values, and guiding visions of the individual who crafted them.&nbsp;In this hands-on workshop, you’ll learn about the purpose and symbolism of Medicine Shields and be guided through the process of designing and assembling your own. Each participant will create their shield using a brass ring as the frame and locally sourced deer hide as the canvas. You’ll then personalize it using beads, feathers, and meaningful symbols&nbsp;that reflect your personal story, values, and aspirations.</p>
<p>Alongside the creative process, this session also includes important conversations around the Medicine Wheel teachings, appropriate terminology&nbsp;when speaking about Indigenous Peoples, and the Truth and Reconciliation Commission’s 94 Calls to Action, offering an opportunity to deepen your understanding of Indigenous history, identity, and the path forward.</p>
<p>This workshop is delivered in a safe and inclusive space that encourages respectful dialogue, learning, and connection. No prior experience is necessary, all materials are provided, and participants of all backgrounds are welcome.</p>
<p>This workshop will take place outdoors; an indoor space will be provided in the event of inclement weather.&nbsp; Light refreshments will be served.</p>
<p><strong>About the instructor:&nbsp;</strong>Makatew Workshops was founded in 2019 by Marc Forgette, a French Algonquin member of the Apitipi Anicinapek Nation (formerly Wahgoshig First Nation). Marc facilitates cultural awareness workshops for public, private, and non-profit organizations, with a hands-on approach that emphasizes respectful engagement and meaningful dialogue.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<strong>Notes:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The primary language of delivery for this program is English.</li>
<li>There are two accessible parking spaces located in the parking lot closest to the museum. The workshop will take place outside on a grass lawn and under sun cover, or inside the museum on the main floor. There is an accessible bathroom located via gravel path. Additional&nbsp;<a href="https://ottawa.ca/en/node/1007490/">information about accessibility</a>&nbsp;can be found on the museum web page. If you have questions or concerns regarding accessibility, please contact the museum by phone at 613-832-4347 or by email at&nbsp;<a href="mailto:museums@ottawa.ca">museums@ottawa.ca</a>.</li>
<li>Advance registration is required. Workshops with insufficient registration may be cancelled. If an alternative cannot be offered, a refund will be issued.</li>
<li>Visit the&nbsp;<a href="https://ottawa.ca/en/family-and-social-services/older-adults/financial-assistance#section-89551f56-14c3-4f6e-b24c-5e5072350977">Ottawa Hand in Hand</a>&nbsp;web page for information on available financial supports to facilitate participation in recreation and culture programs.</li>
</ul>
